00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:13.809
Marcin Bugaj: So, hi everyone.

148
00:19:14.370 --> 00:19:20.680
Marcin Bugaj: update on Project 3, which is CKVM Guest API standardization.

149
00:19:20.930 --> 00:19:27.129
Marcin Bugaj: Today we are doing a recap on the standards that are accepted and that are in review.

150
00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:31.720
Marcin Bugaj: And discuss to… Vendor results…

151
00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:42.159
Marcin Bugaj: So we now have 8 accepted standards. They cover Isa input output crypto accelerators.

152
00:19:42.510 --> 00:19:45.839
Marcin Bugaj: Termination, memory ownership, safety traps.

153
00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:51.189
Marcin Bugaj: And, accepted since the last call, the static library and tinker script.

154
00:19:51.760 --> 00:20:01.530
Marcin Bugaj: Two standards are open for your review at the amber ones at the bottom of the page. Health loading and accelerated memory operations.

155
00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:11.849
Marcin Bugaj: I'll go deeper on health loading now, because it changed the most since it was announced on the last call.

156
00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:21.539
Marcin Bugaj: This standard defines one precise deterministic way to turn a guest elf into the initial machine state.

157
00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:27.500
Marcin Bugaj: how to validate the header, load the segments and check the entry point.

158
00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:34.009
Marcin Bugaj: The big change since the last time is what an executable segment actually means.

159
00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:49.420
Marcin Bugaj: The executable and readable flags were left open to the interpretation. The ABI document for RISC-V and in general doesn't say what these flags imply in practice, and we nailed that down.

160
00:20:49.620 --> 00:20:57.119
Marcin Bugaj: There are two clear options how to interpret readable and executable flags.

161
00:20:58.030 --> 00:21:05.950
Marcin Bugaj: So… Execute flag, execute only means that segments holds instructions and nothing else.

162
00:21:06.260 --> 00:21:12.380
Marcin Bugaj: If the program tries to read it as data, That is an abnormal termination.

163
00:21:12.600 --> 00:21:16.309
Marcin Bugaj: And the second interpretation is execute and read.

164
00:21:16.660 --> 00:21:20.839
Marcin Bugaj: which is that bytes can be both run and read.

165
00:21:21.180 --> 00:21:24.759
Marcin Bugaj: And a load returns the real bytes.

166
00:21:25.170 --> 00:21:28.630
Marcin Bugaj: Here, read-only data can safely sit next to the code.

167
00:21:31.700 --> 00:21:46.869
Marcin Bugaj: zkVMs can support only one of those. So that's an inherent property of a zkVM. And our recommendation is to accept the latter, execute and read.

168
00:21:47.050 --> 00:21:53.209
Marcin Bugaj: Because no toolchain can promise you a clean instruction-only code section.

169
00:21:53.540 --> 00:22:00.099
Marcin Bugaj: And a stray jump table can always slip in to the executable segment.

170
00:22:00.740 --> 00:22:01.800
Marcin Bugaj: Yeah.

171
00:22:02.420 --> 00:22:11.730
Marcin Bugaj: That didn't happen when we compiled Reth and other programs which can execute successfully on Zisk.

172
00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:21.629
Marcin Bugaj: And Zisk implements the first interpretation, in which case the executable segment cannot be read.

173
00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:28.230
Marcin Bugaj: So, that didn't happen, but in general, the compilers

174
00:22:28.580 --> 00:22:31.440
Marcin Bugaj: There is no such guarantee that

175
00:22:31.650 --> 00:22:41.879
Marcin Bugaj: compiler emits text section without data incorporated in it. So there are flags to control it. But in general

176
00:22:42.610 --> 00:22:45.339
Marcin Bugaj: It's it's it's just it's discouraged.

177
00:22:45.620 --> 00:22:52.960
Marcin Bugaj: to, to have a Zkvm. That is, that cannot read.

178
00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:54.980
Marcin Bugaj: the executable segment.

179
00:22:57.700 --> 00:23:01.499
Marcin Bugaj: Now the 2 results.

180
00:23:01.910 --> 00:23:12.190
Marcin Bugaj: 1st output. The I/O standard says that public output can be of arbitrary length. You can call write output as many times as you want.

181
00:23:12.410 --> 00:23:15.970
Marcin Bugaj: and the bytes will just be concatenated.

182
00:23:17.090 --> 00:23:22.620
Marcin Bugaj: BLA, M I implemented that on this in this Pr.

183
00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:29.350
Marcin Bugaj: As the bytes are written to write outputs, they are hashed on the fly into a running digest.

184
00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:34.909
Marcin Bugaj: And only that digest is committed to the proof. The output bytes travel alongside the proof.

185
00:23:35.150 --> 00:23:37.850
Marcin Bugaj: So the verifier can rehash them.

186
00:23:38.110 --> 00:23:42.460
Marcin Bugaj: and check that they match the committed digest.

187
00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:49.639
Marcin Bugaj: You know, So, the takeaway is on the right.

188
00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:54.830
Marcin Bugaj: Today, only SP1 and Zisk support, support standard compliant

189
00:23:55.060 --> 00:23:59.089
Marcin Bugaj: arbitrary length outputs, other ZKVMs don't.

190
00:24:01.490 --> 00:24:04.130
Marcin Bugaj: second result.

191
00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:10.640
Marcin Bugaj: is that the standard gives the whole heap to the application.

192
00:24:11.150 --> 00:24:15.350
Marcin Bugaj: That has a consequence that a vendor can miss.

193
00:24:15.600 --> 00:24:22.609
Marcin Bugaj: The precompiles in your static library must not allocate in the guest heap.

194
00:24:23.180 --> 00:24:29.329
Marcin Bugaj: As on the top bar, that's a collision to fix, shown on the bottom bar.

195
00:24:30.330 --> 00:24:38.440
Marcin Bugaj: A separate isolated scratch region is needed to implement dynamic allocation for precompiles.

196
00:24:38.870 --> 00:24:45.600
Marcin Bugaj: On this, that's a small bump allocator reset on every call to a precompile.

197
00:24:46.260 --> 00:24:51.179
Marcin Bugaj: Other vendors should check whether the same collision affects them.

198
00:24:53.670 --> 00:24:59.270
Marcin Bugaj: Last, a direction that we want to flag, and it may become a standard.

199
00:24:59.850 --> 00:25:04.930
Marcin Bugaj: Ethereum Guests should be built with a stock on unmodified toolchains.

200
00:25:05.260 --> 00:25:18.200
Marcin Bugaj: The reason is trust. A modified compiler grows the trusted computing base, and even small patch to the compiler puts the correctness of all the emitted code in question.

201
00:25:18.860 --> 00:25:23.689
Marcin Bugaj: Yes, a modified compiler could produce better code tuned for a ZKVM.

202
00:25:23.810 --> 00:25:27.000
Marcin Bugaj: We give that up on the purpose.

203
00:25:27.120 --> 00:25:34.079
Marcin Bugaj: A ZKVM can absorb those cost differences, and correctness matters more than speed.

