388
00:50:42.190 --> 00:50:52.970
ben: What I got was about 42% of combined speed up for all of the changes, plus some other side quests that I worked on.

389
00:50:53.450 --> 00:51:03.829
ben: So what I noticed that worked was really making sure that applying all of the hash precompiles works correctly and all of the instances.

390
00:51:04.200 --> 00:51:07.930
ben: are… are… We're calling that.

391
00:51:08.090 --> 00:51:11.690
ben: This was one of the… one of the biggest speed-up.

392
00:51:12.490 --> 00:51:23.300
ben: And then also making sure that we are using only the things that are necessary. So things like parallelism and locks.

393
00:51:23.590 --> 00:51:29.479
ben: are adding just some overheads to the Guest Programs, which is completely unnecessary.

394
00:51:30.390 --> 00:51:37.120
ben: And finally, also being more cautious about how we handle memory, how we store types, and…

395
00:51:37.490 --> 00:51:39.729
ben: If we do not allocate

396
00:51:40.150 --> 00:51:53.109
ben: unreasonably. The last one, which I didn't count to the combined speedup, is applying some zkVM specific instructions. So as Ignacio mentioned.

397
00:51:53.300 --> 00:51:59.610
ben: There has been already some effort for comparing the 256 Arithmetic and CISC

398
00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:03.100
ben: I also need to do some more measurements on this.

399
00:52:04.390 --> 00:52:13.750
ben: And as for the other things that I worked on was standardizing the serialization for

400
00:52:14.040 --> 00:52:19.160
ben: for ethrex, which makes it much closer to the specifications.

401
00:52:19.940 --> 00:52:25.340
ben: And additionally looking into relatively new paper for.

402
00:52:25.560 --> 00:52:37.519
