406
00:53:08.070 --> 00:53:23.939
ben: So I tested it on the mainnet blocks and also EST fixtures, and I believe the EST results are more interesting here. So what we have here is there are brewing costs on the y-axis.

407
00:53:23.970 --> 00:53:31.419
ben: And then here you can see different types of allocators. So there is BAM, BLMalloc, TALC, and TLFS.

408
00:53:31.760 --> 00:53:39.349
ben: And we can already see the first instance for OM on some of the just few selected tests.

409
00:53:39.590 --> 00:53:50.219
ben: And also the second thing to notice is that for almost all of the tests that I run is that BAM is naturally the most efficient because it doesn't free.

410
00:53:50.360 --> 00:53:57.149
ben: And then all of the other allocators are arranged more or less in this order.

411
00:53:57.980 --> 00:54:05.119
ben: Then we can also evaluate what is the highest address that is touched by the memory.

412
00:54:06.080 --> 00:54:16.889
ben: Unsurprisingly, bump is consuming much more of the memory. Here we can see that this one that is touching the threshold is the one that OMs.

413
00:54:17.610 --> 00:54:21.559
ben: And then there are two other tests that are dangerously close.

414
00:54:22.250 --> 00:54:27.610
ben: And as for the usage for all of the other allocators.

415
00:54:28.740 --> 00:54:37.380
ben: They are having more or less the same performance on what is the highest memory address that they touch.

416
00:54:39.160 --> 00:54:39.979
ben: Yeah, so…

417
00:54:40.270 --> 00:54:45.770
ben: And then when we push this further, we can notice that two of these tests that are close.

418
00:54:45.890 --> 00:54:50.590
ben: for 200 million gas limits.

419
00:54:50.880 --> 00:54:54.280
ben: These are the ones that, fail.

420
00:54:54.410 --> 00:54:55.620
ben: So…

421
00:54:55.830 --> 00:55:11.779
ben: considering higher gas limits, there can be more problems. And one thing that we can tackle this problem is that we can increase the memory that's given to the bump allocator from around half gigabyte, which is currently

422
00:55:11.780 --> 00:55:19.969
ben: to one and a half. So this is the blue column that we have here. And these are, again, the proving costs.

423
00:55:20.360 --> 00:55:21.940
ben: On… on the tests.

424
00:55:22.540 --> 00:55:29.279
ben: And… Once we increase the memory for the BAM allocator, we can see that we bypass the problem.

425
00:55:29.720 --> 00:55:37.779
ben: And also that for the DL malloc and the increased bump, the proving costs are more or less similar.

426
00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:44.650
ben: But then, looking again at the highest memory address touched.

427
00:55:44.980 --> 00:55:51.010
ben: You can see that there's, again, a big difference, so…

428
00:55:51.150 --> 00:56:08.349
ben: Yeah, I'm not sure how far in the guest limit are we targeting for the upcoming protocol changes, but definitely, like, if there is only one block that results in failed proving, that this can be used as an attack vector, so…

429
00:56:08.470 --> 00:56:18.090
ben: Even though we are able to bypass the problem by increasing memory, I think it's important to consider…

430
00:56:18.250 --> 00:56:25.360
ben: using some more sophisticated allocator, like the analog, for the safety reasons.

